        intermediateContent:
          'Friction is calculated using **f = μN**, where μ is the coefficient of friction and N is the normal force. Static friction: **f_s ≤ μ_s × N** (it can be any value up to the maximum). Kinetic friction: **f_k = μ_k × N** (constant once sliding). Typical μ values: rubber on dry concrete ≈ 0.8, ice on ice ≈ 0.03, steel on steel ≈ 0.6. Example: A 50 kg box on a floor with μ_s = 0.4. Normal force N = mg = 50 × 9.8 = 490 N. Maximum static friction = 0.4 × 490 = **196 N** — you need more than 196 N to start the box moving. Once sliding with μ_k = 0.3: f_k = 0.3 × 490 = **147 N** of resistance. On an incline at angle θ, the component of gravity along the slope is mg sin θ and friction is μ mg cos θ. The box slides when **tan θ > μ_s**.',
