        title: 'Echolocation — Seeing with Sound',
        beginnerContent:
          'Bats and dolphins navigate and hunt using echolocation: they emit high-frequency sound pulses and listen for the echoes that bounce back from objects. By analysing the time delay, intensity, and frequency shift of the returning echoes, their brains build a detailed three-dimensional map of their surroundings. The Gangetic river dolphins of the Brahmaputra have taken this to an extreme — they are essentially blind, with tiny eyes that can only detect light and dark. They rely almost entirely on echolocation to navigate the muddy, silt-heavy waters of the river, finding fish and avoiding obstacles using sound alone. Their echolocation is so precise that they can detect a thin wire in murky water.',
        intermediateContent:
          'Echolocation range depends on the equation **d = (v × t) / 2**, where v is sound speed and t is the round-trip time. Sound in air travels at ~343 m/s; in water at ~1,480 m/s. If a bat receives an echo 5.8 ms after calling, the target is 343 × 0.0058 / 2 = **1.0 m** away. Bats emit pulses at 20–200 kHz, with wavelengths of 1.7–17 mm, allowing them to resolve objects as small as a mosquito wing. As a bat closes on prey, it increases pulse rate from ~10/s to over **200/s** (the "terminal buzz"), improving temporal resolution. Dolphins emit broadband clicks at 20–130 kHz with peak energies of **220 dB re 1 μPa** — among the loudest sounds produced by any animal. They detect targets using the time difference of arrival between echoes at their two ears (interaural time difference ~30 μs) and amplitude differences shaped by the fat-filled lower jaw.',
