        intermediateContent:
          'Indicators work because they are **weak acids or bases** whose protonated and deprotonated forms have different colors. For a generic indicator HIn (colored form A) ⇌ H⁺ + In⁻ (colored form B), the **Henderson-Hasselbalch equation** applies: pH = pKa + log([In⁻]/[HIn]). When pH = pKa, [In⁻] = [HIn] and you see a 50/50 mix of both colors — the **transition point**. The visible color change spans roughly **pKa ± 1** (the transition range). Phenolphthalein: pKa ≈ 9.4, transition range 8.2-10.0. Methyl orange: pKa ≈ 3.7, range 3.1-4.4. **Universal indicator** is a mixture of ~5 indicators with staggered pKa values, covering the full 1-14 range with continuous color changes.',
        advancedContent:
          'The **anthocyanin** pigments in red cabbage (and hydrangeas, blueberries, and many flowers) are **flavylium cations** that undergo structural changes with pH. At pH < 3, the flavylium cation (AH⁺, red) dominates. At pH 4-5, the carbinol pseudobase (colorless) forms. At pH 6-7, the quinoidal base (purple) appears. At pH 8-9, the anionic quinoidal base (blue-green) dominates. Above pH 11, the chalcone form (yellow) takes over. These are not simple protonation/deprotonation events — they involve ring-opening, hydration, and tautomerism. Modern analytical chemistry uses **pH-sensitive fluorescent probes** (SNARF, BCECF) that shift excitation/emission wavelengths with pH, enabling real-time pH imaging inside living cells with confocal microscopy. Researchers use these to study how cancer cells maintain an acidic microenvironment (pH ~6.5) around tumors while keeping intracellular pH normal (~7.4).',
