        intermediateContent:
          'Primality testing for large numbers uses probabilistic methods. The Miller-Rabin test checks whether a^(n-1) ≡ 1 (mod n) for random bases a. If the test fails, n is definitely composite. If it passes for k random bases, n is "probably prime" with error probability < 4^(-k). For k = 20 tests, the chance of a false positive is < 10^(-12). The AKS algorithm (2002) proved that deterministic primality testing can be done in polynomial time — but Miller-Rabin remains faster in practice. RSA-2048, the current standard for secure communication, uses two 1024-bit primes (~308 digits each).',
